==English==

===Etymology===
First attested in 1583. From {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|abruptus||broken off}}, perfect passive participle of {{m|la|abrumpō||break off}}, formed from {{m|la|ab||from, away from}} + {{m|la|rumpō||to break}}.<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=8}}</ref><ref>{{R:MW3 1976|page=6}}</ref>

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ə.bɹʌpt/|/aˈbɹʌpt/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|En-us-abrupt.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|ʌpt|lang=en}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj|more|er}}

# {{lb|en|obsolete|rare}} Broken away (from restraint). {{defdate|Attested only in the late 16th century.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=8}}</ref>
# Without notice to prepare the mind for the event; [[sudden]]; [[hasty]]; [[unceremonious]]. {{defdate|First attested in the late 16th century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: {{ux|en|The party came to an '''abrupt''' end when the parents of our host arrived.}}
#* {{quote-book|author={{w|William Shakespeare}}|title=Henry VI Part I|section=II-iii|passage=The cause of your '''abrupt''' departure.|year=1592}}
# [[curt|Curt]] in manner; [[brusque]]; [[rude]]; [[uncivil]]; [[impolite]]. {{defdate|First attested in the late 16th century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# Having sudden [[transitions]] from one subject or state to another; [[unconnected]]; disjointed. {{defdate|First attested in the late 16th century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{quote-book|author={{w|Ben Jonson}}|passage=The '''abrupt''' style, which hath many breaches.}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} Broken off. {{defdate|Attested from the early 17th century until the mid 18th century.}}<ref name =SOED/>
# Extremely [[steep]] or [[craggy]] as if broken up; [[precipitous]]. {{defdate|First attested in the early 17th century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{quote-book|author={{w|Thomson}}|passage=Tumbling through ricks '''abrupt'''.}}
# {{lb|en|botany}} Suddenly [[terminating]], as if [[cut off]]; [[truncate]]. {{defdate|First attested in the early 19th century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: {{rfquotek|Gray}}

